4;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/apple-watch-series-9-may-finally-get-a-new-processor-151516259.html">更快的处理器</a>和一些新颜色。预计其所有型号都将保持与 Series 8 相同的尺寸，总体而言，升级将是有限的。</p>本文最初发表在 Engadget 上，网址为 https://www.engadget.com/apple-watch-x-will-reportedly-feature-a-thinner-casing-and-Magnetic-bands-092419190.html?src=rss]] >; </description><link/><![CDATA[https://www.engadget.com/apple-watch-x-will-reportedly-feature-a-thinner-casing-and-magnetic-bands-092419190.html?src=rss]]><source_id> engadget_479</source_id><guid ispermalink="false"> c41c74d4-10ed-4299-acee-f2874f0b7c1e</guid><dc:creator>萨拉·菲尔丁</dc:creator><source/><![CDATA[Engadget]]><dc:publisher>恩杰特</dc:publisher><dc:rightsholder>恩杰特</dc:rightsholder><pubDate>Mon, 14 Aug 2023 09:24:19 +0000</pubDate><ingested> 1692005406</ingested><modified> 2023-08-14T09:30:11+00:00 </modified><category><![CDATA[site|engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[provider_name|Engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[region|US]]></category><category><![CDATA[language|en-US]]></category><category><![CDATA[author_name|Sarah Fielding]]></category><media:content height="1267" medium="image" url="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-07/096bfbe0-19b9-11ee-bc3f-e04acc4cbdd8" width="2000"><media:keywords>标题</media:keywords><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[1]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[ ]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[ ]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[ ]]></media:title></media:content><media:content height="1267" medium="image" url="https://media-mbst-pub-ue1.s3.amazonaws.com/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-07/096bfbe0-19b9-11ee-bc3f-e04acc4cbdd8" width="2000"><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[2]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[Apple]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[A hand fiddling with the Apple Watch 8.]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[Apple Watch Series 8]]></media:title></media:content></item><item><title><![CDATA[Hitting the Books: The thirty-year quest to make WiFi a connectivity reality]]></title><description type="html"><![CDATA[<p>如果没有 Wi-Fi 互联网提供的近乎无处不在的连接，现代消费科技世界就不会存在。它作为连接我们的移动设备和智能家电的无线链路，支持我们的流媒体娱乐并将我们连接到全球互联网。</p><p> Greg Ennis 在他的新书《 <a data-i13n="elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:;cpos:1;pos:1" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsInN0b3JlSWQiOiI2NmVhNTY3YS1jOTg3LTRjMmUtYTJmZi0wMjkwNGVmZGU2ZWEiLCJsYW5kaW5nVXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYW1hem9uLmNvbS9CZXlvbmQtRXZlcnl3aGVyZS1CZWNhbWUtQmVsb3ZlZC1UZWNobm9sb2d5LWVib29rL2RwL0IwQ0MzSE1MMVI_dGFnPWdkZ3QwYy1wLW8tMXQxLTIwIiwiY29udGVudFV1aWQiOiI0NGM0NWJkYS1jZThlLTQyY2EtYmZiZi03NDBlMTM4Nzk0MGQifQ&amp;signature=AQAAAaoxYlnYgQcwvVOhSdcDq6CFLUjR1SEwPCyfHzq4S5zJ&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FBeyond-Everywhere-Became-Beloved-Technology-ebook%2Fdp%2FB0CC3HML1R" class="rapid-with-clickid"><em>超越无处不在：Wi-Fi 如何成为世界上最受欢迎的技术》</em></a>中，共同撰写了该提案，该提案成为 WiFi 技术的技术基础，之后创立了 Wi-Fi 联盟并担任其技术副总裁四分之一个世纪以来，引导读者了解这种如今日常技术的迷人（有时令人沮丧）的起源。在下面的摘录中，Ennis 回顾了最终说服 IEEE 802.11 无线 LAN 标准委员会采用其候选协议之前痛苦的最后几天的推介和演示，并检查了以太网、标准和以太网的发明者 Bob Metcalf 的外部影响。科技公司 3Com 促成了 Wi-Fi 的最终出现。 </p><span id="end-legacy-contents"></span><figure><img src="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-08/4b05dd60-321d-11ee-bebb-05ef993eac11" style="height:1500px;width:2000px;" alt="蓝底白字 V 是 WiFi 信号强度指示器" data-uuid="7c4a41b8-6ed5-3cde-b8bc-abdd8ca6bbf0"><figcaption></figcaption><div class="photo-credit">波斯特希尔出版社</div></figure><p>摘自<a data-i13n="cpos:2;pos:1" href="https://posthillpress.com/book/beyond-everywhere-how-wi-fi-became-the-worlds-most-beloved-technology"><em>《超越一切：Wi-Fi 如何成为世界上最受欢迎的技术</em></a>(c) 2023》，作者：Greg Ennis。由波斯特希尔出版社出版。经许可使用。</p><hr><p>现在选择我们的 DFWMAC 基金会后，IEEE 委员会的工作就平静下来，进入了批准该标准的实际文本语言的深思熟虑的过程。仍然有一些大的空白需要填补——最重要的是加密方案——但委员会已经习惯了开发最终标准文件的 MAC 部分的草案版本。在 1994 年 1 月在圣何塞举行的会议上，我与 Bob O&#39;Hara 一起被选为整个（MAC+PHY）标准的技术编辑，我们两人将继续担任编辑，直至最终版本的首次出版。 1997年标准。</p><p> MAC 部分的初稿基本上是我们重新格式化为 IEEE 模板的 DFWMAC 规范。文本的制定是 IEEE 标准委员会内部既定的流程：当鲍勃和我完成草案时，委员会成员将提交评论，在随后的会议上，将就改进文本进行辩论和决定。文本。数据包格式发生了变化，并且为协议的操作开发了详细的算法语言，但总的来说，DFWMAC 的概念框架保持不变。事实上，DFWMAC 首次提出近三十年后，其核心思想继续构成 Wi-Fi 的基础。</p><p>当这个文本最终确定过程正在进行时，该技术拒绝停滞不前。无线电通信理论和电路设计的进步意味着更高的速度可能会超出标准草案中 2 兆位的最大值。甚至在 1997 年最初的标准最终正式采用之前，行业内的许多公司就开始考虑更高的速度。实现超过 10 兆比特的速度（与标准以太网相当）已成为无线 LAN 行业的圣杯。面临的挑战是在满足联邦通信委员会要求的同时做到这一点——这需要科学和艺术。</p><p>当然，速度越快越好，但是是什么推动了 10 兆比特的发展呢？哪些无线应用真正需要 10 兆位速度？ 20 世纪 90 年代无线 LAN 的主要应用是所谓的“垂直应用”，例如，Symbol 的安装涉及用于库存管理的手持式条形码扫描仪。这种专用无线网络由垂直整合的系统提供商安装，提供完整的服务包，包括硬件、软件、应用程序、培训和支持，因此有“垂直”术语。虽然 10 兆位速度对于这些垂直应用来说是不错的，但可能没有必要，而且如果成本上升，这样的速度就不合理了。因此，推动这种速度需求的是所谓的“横向”市场——通用计算机的无线连接。特别是，主要基于以太网的办公自动化市场（PC 连接到共享打印机和文件服务器）被认为需要比 IEEE 标准的 2 兆位更快的速度。</p><p>鲍勃·梅特卡夫 (Bob Metcalfe) 在计算机行业因三件事而闻名：以太网、梅特卡夫定律和 3Com。他共同发明了以太网；这很简单，这本身就是他成名的理由。梅特卡夫定律——当然，它实际上不是物理定律，但似乎具有真正的解释力——指出通信技术的价值与连接设备数量的平方成正比。这个直观上合理的“定律”解释了网络技术日益普及所产生的病毒式滚雪球效应。但此刻进入我们 Wi-Fi 故事的将是梅特卡夫的 3Com。</p><p>梅特卡夫在 PARC（施乐帕洛阿尔托研究中心）工作时发明了以太网。 PARC 在开发当今许多最重要的技术方面发挥了关键作用，除了以太网之外，还包括基于窗口的图形计算机接口和激光打印。但施乐以《摸索未来》而闻名，这也是一本 1999 年出版的书的书名，该书记录了“施乐如何发明了第一台个人电脑，然后被忽视”，因为在帕洛阿尔托研究中心开发的创新通常最终不是由施乐而是由苹果实现商业化和别的。毫不奇怪，梅特卡夫决定需要一家不同的公司将他的以太网发明推向市场，并于 1979 年与一些合作伙伴成立了 3C​​om。</p><p>同年我加入了 Sytek，该公司成立于几个月前。与 3Com 一样，Sytek 也专注于 LAN 产品，尽管与 3Com 的以太网相比，它基于宽带有线电视技术。但 Sytek 专注于硬件，而 3Com 决定也开发自己的软件，支持新的基于 LAN 的办公应用程序，以共享 PC 访问数据文件和打印机。凭借这些软件产品与其以太网技术的结合，3Com 在个人计算机推出后的九十年代成为蓬勃发展的办公自动化市场的主导者。鲍勃·梅特卡夫 (Bob Metcalfe) 对无线局域网持怀疑态度是出了名的。在 1993 年 8 月 16 日的《InfoWorld》杂志上，他在题为“无线计算将永久失败”的文章中写下了自己的观点：</p><blockquote><p>这并不是说不会有任何无线计算。无线移动计算机最终将像今天的无管道移动浴室一样普遍。飞机、船上、建筑工地、摇滚音乐会以及其他不方便铺设管道的地方都可以找到便携式便盆。但浴室仍然主要是管道式的。出于或多或少相同的原因，计算机将保持有线状态。</p></blockquote><p>他将无线设备与便携式便盆进行比较只是酸葡萄心理吗？毕竟，这是来自以太网（有线网络的原型）的发明者。无论如何，我们很幸运，梅特卡夫在 1996 年不再参与 3Com 的管理，因为 3Com 现在作为 Wi-Fi 发展的主要催化剂进入我们的故事。</p><p> 3Com 的无线 LAN 战略自然引起了人们极大的兴趣，因为无论他们决定采取什么方向，都将成为市场的一个重要因素。作为拥有习惯于 10 兆位速度的客户群的一流以太网公司，很明显，除非无线速度提高到超过 IEEE 标准草案的 2 兆位，否则他们不会采取任何措施。但他们是否会像鲍勃·梅特卡夫（Bob Metcalfe）建议的那样，决定完全远离无线领域，而专注于有线以太网的强大市场地位？如果他们确实决定加入无线世界，他们会开发自己的技术来实现这一目标吗？或者他们会与现有的无线开发商合作吗？ The task of navigating 3Com through this twisted path would fall to a disarmingly boyish business development whiz named Jeff Abramowitz, who approached me one afternoon quite unexpectedly.</p><p> Jeff tapped me on the shoulder at an IEEE meeting. “Hey, Greg, can I talk with you for a sec?” he whispered, and we both snuck quietly out of the meeting room. “Just wondering if you have any time available to take on a new project.” He didn&#39;t even give me a chance to respond before continuing with a smile: “10 megabits. Wireless Ethernet.” The idea of working with the foremost Ethernet company on a high-speed version of 802.11 obviously enticed me, and I quickly said, “Let&#39;s get together next week.”</p><p> He told me that they had already made some progress towards an internally developed implementation, but that in his opinion, it was more promising for them to partner with one of the major active players. 3Com wanted to procure a complete system of  wireless LAN products that they could offer to their customer base, comprising access points and plug-in adapters (“client devices”) for both laptops and desktops. There would need to be a Request for Proposal developed, which would, of course, include both technical and business requirements, and Jeff looked to me to help formulate the technical requirements. The potential partners included Symbol, Lucent, Aironet, InTalk, and Harris Semiconductor, among others, and our first task was to develop this RFP to send out to these companies.</p><p> Symbol should need no introduction, having been my client and having played a major role in the development of the DFWMAC protocol that was selected as the foundation for the 802.11 standard. Lucent may sound like a new player, but in fact, this is simply our NCR Dutch colleagues from Utrecht — including Wim, Cees, Vic, and Bruce — under a new corporate name, NCR having been first bought by AT&amp;T and then spun off into Lucent. Aironet is similarly an old friend under a new name — back at the start of our story, we saw that the very first wireless LAN product approved by the FCC was from a Canadian company called Telesystems, which eventually was merged into Telxon, with Aironet then being the result of a 1994 spinoff focusing on the wireless LAN business. And in another sign of the small-world nature of the wireless LAN industry at this time, my DFWMAC co-author, Phil Belanger, had moved from Xircom to Aironet in early 1996.</p><p> The two companies here who are truly new to our story are InTalk and Harris. InTalk was a small startup founded in 1996 in Cambridge, England (and then subsequently acquired by Nokia), whose engineers were significant contributors to the development of the final text within the 802.11 standard. Harris Corporation was a major defense contractor headquartered in Melbourne, Florida, who leveraged their radio system design experience into an early wireless LAN chip development project. Since they were focused on being a chip supplier rather than an equipment manufacturer, we didn&#39;t expect them to submit their own proposal, but it was likely that other responders would incorporate their chips, so we certainly viewed them as an important player.</p><p> Over the first couple of months in 1997, Jeff and I worked up a Request for Proposal for 3Com to send out, along with a 3Com engineer named David Fisher, and by March we were able to provide the final version to various candidate partners. Given 3Com&#39;s position in the general LAN market, the level of interest was high, and we indeed got a good set of proposals back from the companies we expected, including Symbol, Lucent, InTalk, and Aironet. These companies, along with Harris, quickly became our focus, and we began a process of intense engagement with all of them over the next several months, building relationships in the process that a year later would ultimately lead to the formation of the Wi-Fi Alliance.</p><p> Bob Metcalfe&#39;s wireless skepticism had been soundly rejected by the very company he founded, with 3Com instead adopting the mantle of wireless evangelism. And Wireless Ethernet, soon to be christened Wi-Fi, was destined to outshine its wired LAN ancestor.</p> This article originally appeared on Engadget at https://www.engadget.com/hitting-the-books-beyond-everywhere-greg-ennis-post-hill-press-143010153.html?src=rss]]>; </description><link/><![CDATA[https://www.engadget.com/hitting-the-books-beyond-everywhere-greg-ennis-post-hill-press-143010153.html?src=rss]]><source_id> engadget_479</source_id><guid ispermalink="false"> 44c45bda-ce8e-42ca-bfbf-740e1387940d</guid><dc:creator> Andrew Tarantola</dc:creator><source/><![CDATA[Engadget]]><dc:publisher> Engadget</dc:publisher><dc:rightsholder> Engadget</dc:rightsholder><pubDate> Sun, 13 Aug 2023 14:30:10 +0000</pubDate><ingested> 1691701382</ingested><modified> 2023-08-10T21:03:16+00:00 </modified><category><![CDATA[Technology & Electronics]]></category><category><![CDATA[site|engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[provider_name|Engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[region|US]]></category><category><![CDATA[language|en-US]]></category><category><![CDATA[author_name|Andrew Tarantola]]></category><media:content height="4723" medium="image" url="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-07/bd2cc6a0-321e-11ee-adbf-93e7fb9ff1ab" width="6140"><media:keywords> headline </media:keywords><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[1]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[ ]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[ ]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[ ]]></media:title></media:content><media:content height="1389" medium="image" url="https://media-mbst-pub-ue1.s3.amazonaws.com/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-08/1d5133e0